  "prompt": "How can you determine the Lewis structure of so3?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of SO3 (sulfur trioxide), follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the total number of valence electrons:\n- Sulfur (S): 6 valence electrons\n- Oxygen (O): 6 valence electrons \u00d7 3 = 18\n- Total valence electrons: 6 + 18 = 24\n\n2. Arrange atoms:\n- Put sulfur in the center\n- Place three oxygen atoms around sulfur\n\n3. Connect atoms with single bonds:\n- Draw single bonds between sulfur and each oxygen\n\n4. Distribute remaining electrons as lone pairs:\n- Complete octets for oxygen atoms first\n- Place remaining electrons around sulfur\n\n5. Check formal charges:\n- Calculate formal charges for each atom\n- Aim for the lowest possible formal charges\n- Resonance structures may be possible\n\n6. Final Lewis structure:\n- Three resonance structures with double bonds between sulfur and oxygen\n- Electrons distributed to minimize formal charges\n- Trigonal planar molecular geometry\n\nThe Lewis structure shows sulfur bonded to three oxygen atoms with multiple resonance structures, reflecting the molecule's actual electronic configuration.",
